Fill and boil your kettle. Pour the water into a large #saucepan{}. Pop your pan on high heat, add @salt{0.5%tsp} and bring back to the boil.

Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}). Finely chop the @chives{1%bunch} or snip with #scissors{}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} over high heat. When hot, add the @king prawns{180%g} and cook until the prawns start to turn pink, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Meanwhile, when the water is boiling, add the @fresh tagliatelle{198%g} and cook for ~{4%minutes}. Once cooked add the @baby spinach{125%g} to the #colander{}, drain the pasta in the colander (the boiling water will wilt the spinach).

Once the prawns have started to turn pink, add in the garlic and the @chilli flakes{1/5%tsp} (only add a pinch - they're hot!), cook, stirring continuously for ~{1%minute}.

Add the @tomato and olive caper sauce{1%serving}, @tomato passata{1%tin}, @water{50%ml} into the prawns along with half the @hard Italian style cheese{40%g}(grated), bring to the boil and remove from the heat. Taste season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} if you feel it needs it.

> IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Once drained, add the pasta to the sauce and toss together.

Serve between your bowls. Sprinkle over the chives and remaining cheese. Enjoy!

> When a dish this delicious is on the table in 10 minutes, you know you've struck gold. Packed with juicy prawns and fresh tomato sauce, our velvety tagliatelle is about to become your favourite quick-fix recipe. Buon appetito!